# UI/UX Design Standards for AI Coding Agent

## File Structure & Organization

- **@/frontend** - All frontend files and components
- **@/frontend/components/** - Reusable UI components
- **@/frontend/pages/** - Page-level components
- **@/frontend/styles/** - CSS/SCSS files and styling
- **@/frontend/assets/** - Images, icons, and static assets
- **@/frontend/utils/** - Frontend utility functions
- **@/frontend/hooks/** - Custom React hooks
- **@/frontend/types/** - TypeScript type definitions

## Core Design Principles

### 1. Visual Hierarchy & Layout

- **ALWAYS** establish clear visual hierarchy using size, color, and spacing
- **MUST** use CSS Grid and Flexbox for responsive layouts
- **REQUIRED** to use relative units (rem, em, %) instead of fixed pixels
- **ENSURE** sufficient contrast ratios (minimum 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text)

### 2. Responsive Design (Mobile-First)

- **START** with mobile design, then scale up to desktop
- **IMPLEMENT** these breakpoints: 320px, 768px, 1024px, 1440px
- **USE** touch-friendly targets (minimum 44x44px)
- **ENSURE** all interactive elements are accessible on mobile

### 3. Accessibility (WCAG 2.1 AA)

- **MUST** use semantic HTML elements (header, nav, main, section, article, aside, footer)
- **REQUIRED** to include alt text for all images
- **ENSURE** keyboard navigation works for all interactive elements
- **IMPLEMENT** proper ARIA labels and roles
- **TEST** with screen readers

### 4. Color & Typography

- **USE** a consistent color palette with primary, secondary, and accent colors
- **IMPLEMENT** proper color contrast for text readability
- **CHOOSE** readable fonts (system fonts preferred: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI")
- **MAINTAIN** consistent font sizes using rem units

### 5. Component Design Patterns

- **CREATE** reusable components with consistent styling
- **USE** familiar UI patterns (buttons, forms, cards, modals)
- **IMPLEMENT** proper hover and focus states
- **ENSURE** consistent spacing using a design system (8px grid recommended)

### 6. Performance Requirements

- **OPTIMIZE** images with proper srcset and sizes attributes
- **IMPLEMENT** lazy loading for images and non-critical content
- **USE** CSS animations instead of JavaScript when possible
- **MINIMIZE** bundle size with code splitting

### 7. User Experience Guidelines

- **PROVIDE** clear feedback for all user actions (loading states, success/error messages)
- **IMPLEMENT** intuitive navigation patterns
- **ENSURE** forms have inline validation and clear error messages
- **MAINTAIN** consistent terminology throughout the app

## Technical Implementation

### CSS/Styling Standards

- Use CSS custom properties for theming and consistency
- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes for styling
- Maintain consistent spacing using 8px grid system

### HTML Structure Requirements

- Use semantic HTML elements for proper structure
- Include proper ARIA labels and roles
- Implement proper heading hierarchy (h1, h2, h3, etc.)

### JavaScript Interaction Patterns

- Provide keyboard accessibility for all interactive elements
- Implement proper focus management
- Use proper event handling patterns

## Quality Checklist

Before considering any UI complete, verify:

- [ ] Mobile responsive (test on 320px width)
- [ ] Keyboard accessible (Tab navigation works)
- [ ] Screen reader compatible (semantic HTML, ARIA labels)
- [ ] Color contrast meets WCAG standards
- [ ] Touch targets are at least 44x44px
- [ ] Loading states implemented
- [ ] Error handling with user-friendly messages
- [ ] Images optimized and responsive

## Common Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- ❌ Using fixed pixel values instead of relative units
- ❌ Missing alt text for images
- ❌ Non-semantic HTML (divs for everything)
- ❌ Inaccessible forms without proper labels
- ❌ Hard-coded colors instead of CSS variables
- ❌ Missing focus states for interactive elements
- ❌ Poor error handling and user feedback

## Application Rules

- **ALWAYS** apply these standards when creating any user interface
- **MUST** follow accessibility guidelines for all public-facing features
- **REQUIRED** to implement responsive design for all layouts
- **ENSURE** performance optimization for all user-facing code

**Remember: These are not suggestions but requirements for creating professional, accessible, and user-friendly interfaces.**
